          "text": "     1→---\n     2→name: task_management\n     3→description: Gets information on how to work with tasks in this project.\n     4→user-invokable: false\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## What is a task\n     8→Each task is a directory with a name equal to the unique task identifier.\n     9→**Examples:**\n    10→```\n    11→1) Identifier: MUSIC-009 -> Directory .claude/tasks/MUSIC-009/\n    12→2) Identifier: FEED-1000 -> Directory .claude/tasks/FEED-1000/\n    13→```\n    14→\n    15→As mentioned earlier, a task is a directory. It contains a set of .md files. Their set may vary.\n    16→**Example:**\n    17→- task.md - the only mandatory and guaranteed file in a task. Others are optional\n    18→- dev_result.md\n    19→- code_review_result.md\n    20→- qa_review_result.md\n    21→- manual_qa_result.md\n    22→\n    23→## task.md\n    24→File containing main task information:\n    25→- Task identifier\n    26→- Title\n    27→- Problem\n    28→- Task - what needs to be done\n    29→- Constraints\n    30→- Team - which subagents will be included in the work\n    31→- Status - task status. _More about them below_.\n    32→\n    33→> Important: This file is always guaranteed to exist. If it's not there - require the user to create it.\n    34→\n    35→### Task status\n    36→Task status shows progress of each performer:\n    37→- `Ready for dev` - Task waiting for developer to pick it up.\n    38→- `Dev in progress` - Developer has picked up the task.\n    39→- `Ready for review` - Developer has completed work on task. Task waiting for code review.\n    40→- `Review in progress` - Code reviewer has picked up the task.\n    41→- `Ready for qa review` - Code reviewer has completed work on task. Task waiting for QA to pick it up.\n    42→- `QA review in progress` - QA has picked up the task.\n    43→- `Verified` - Work on task is completed.\n    44→\n    45→#### Timestamp\n    46→> Important: Always put date and time next to task status when setting it\n    47→\n    48→Always specify task completion time strictly in format: YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2026-02-25 10:43:00).\n    49→Don't add extra words or explanations before the date.\n    50→\n    51→**Examples:**\n    52→- `Ready for dev` - 2026-02-11 10:43:00\n    53→- `Verified` - 2025-12-24 18:15:43\n    54→\n    55→#### Status workflow process\n    56→```mermaid\n    57→flowchart TD\n    58→\n    59→A[Ready for Dev]\n    60→A --> B[Dev in Progress]\n    61→B --> C[Ready for Review]\n    62→C --> D[Review in Progress]\n    63→D --> E[Ready for QA Review]\n    64→E --> F[QA Review in Progress]\n    65→F --> G[Verified]\n    66→\n    67→%% Rework loops\n    68→C -- changes requested --> A\n    69→F -- bugs found --> A\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→### For performers\n    73→#### Main agent\n    74→Monitors statuses and calls corresponding performers.\n    75→- `Ready for dev` - calls `android-developer` agent.\n    76→- `Ready for review` - calls `android-code-reviewer` agent.\n    77→- `QA review in progress` - calls `qa-expert` agent.\n    78→- `Verified` - work finished. Forming response to user.\n    79→\n    80→**Constraints:**\n    81→- Main agent is prohibited from setting statuses independently. It can only monitor them and call corresponding agents.\n    82→- Prohibited from changing task content\n    83→- Prohibited from moving task to other directories\n    84→\n    85→#### android-developer\n    86→Only monitors statuses related to development.\n    87→If status:\n    88→- `Ready for dev` - Sets new status - `Dev in progress`, because task was picked up.\n    89→- `Dev in progress` - After completing work, changes to `Ready for review`\n    90→\n    91→**Requirements:**\n    92→- Prohibited from changing others' statuses.\n    93→- Flow strictly `Ready for dev` -> Start work -> Set `Dev in progress` -> Finish work -> Set status `Ready for review`\n    94→\n    95→#### android-code-reviewer\n    96→Only monitors statuses related to code review.\n    97→If status:\n    98→- `Ready for review` - Sets new status - `Review in Progress`, because task was picked up.\n    99→- `Review in Progress`\n   100→  - After completing work, if no comments, changes to `Ready for QA Review`\n   101→  - After completing work, if there are comments, sets status `Ready for dev`\n   102→\n   103→**Requirements:**\n   104→- Prohibited from changing others' statuses.\n   105→- Flow strictly `Ready for review` -> Start work -> Set `Review in Progress` -> Finish work -> `Ready for dev` OR `Ready for QA Review`\n   106→\n   107→#### qa-expert\n   108→Only monitors statuses related to code review.\n   109→If status:\n   110→- `Ready for QA Review` - Sets new status - `QA Review in Progress`, because task was picked up.\n   111→- `QA Review in Progress`\n   112→    - After completing work, if no comments, changes to `Verified`\n   113→    - After completing work, if there are comments, sets status `Ready for dev`\n   114→\n   115→**Requirements:**\n   116→- Prohibited from changing others' statuses.\n   117→- Flow strictly `Ready for QA Review` -> Start work -> Set `QA Review in Progress` -> Finish work -> `Ready for dev` OR `Verified`\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n",
