          "text": "     1→---\n     2→name: developer_result\n     3→description: Information necessary for generating a report on completed development work\n     4→user-invokable: false\n     5→disable-model-invocation: true\n     6→---\n     7→\n     8→## Purpose\n     9→Helps developers record the results of work on a task in the form of a clear report that:\n    10→- is easy for reviewers and QA to read\n    11→- clearly answers \"what was done / where / how to verify\"\n    12→- contains risks and technical debt\n    13→- is suitable for change history (release notes, postmortem)\n    14→\n    15→## When to use\n    16→Use this skill:\n    17→- after completing development on a task (before moving to Ready for review / Ready for QA)\n    18→- after fixing bugs based on review/QA comments\n    19→- for any changes that could break builds, flows, analytics, networking, performance\n    20→\n    21→## Input you must ask from user (only if missing)\n    22→If data is missing — ask without hesitation\n    23→If user provided enough information — don't ask questions.\n    24→\n    25→## Output\n    26→Always generate/update file:\n    27→- `dev_result.md` (always next to task/in `.claude/tasks/<task_id>/dev_result.md`)\n    28→- if user explicitly specified a different path — use it\n    29→\n    30→Style: strictly to the point, in English, no fluff.\n    31→\n    32→## Rules\n    33→- Write specifics: module names, classes, methods, flags, keys, endpoints.\n    34→- Don't write \"done/fixed\" without clarifying **what exactly**.\n    35→- Always add a \"How to verify\" block with step-by-step actions.\n    36→- If there's a feature flag/toggle — specify name, default, where to enable.\n    37→- If APIs/contracts/schemas are affected — specify compatibility and migrations.\n    38→- If there are risks/debt — record honestly (but briefly) and suggest follow-up tasks.\n    39→- If many changes — group by subsystems/modules.\n    40→- Don't make things up. If you don't know — mark `TODO:` or ask 1 clarifying question.\n    41→\n    42→## Template (fill-in)\n    43→Use this template as a base:\n    44→\n    45→---\n    46→# Dev Result\n    47→\n    48→## Task\n    49→- ID\n    50→- Context (1-2 sentences):\n    51→\n    52→## Done\n    53→- [ ] (specific change #1)\n    54→- [ ] (specific change #2)\n    55→- [ ] …\n    56→\n    57→## Where changed (code/modules)\n    58→- Modules:\n    59→- Main files/classes:\n    60→- Configs/manifest/gradle:\n    61→\n    62→## Contracts and compatibility\n    63→- API/DTO/DB/protocols:\n    64→- Backward/forward compatibility:\n    65→- Migrations (if any):\n    66→\n    67→## Feature flags / settings\n    68→- Flag:\n    69→  - name:\n    70→  - default:\n    71→  - where to enable:\n    72→  - impact:\n    73→\n    74→## How to verify (manual testing)\n    75→1.\n    76→2.\n    77→3.\n    78→Expected result:\n    79→- …\n    80→\n    81→## Tests\n    82→- Unit tests:\n    83→- Instrumental/screenshots:\n    84→- Manual checks/checklist:\n    85→\n    86→## Logs/metrics/analytics\n    87→- Added/changed:\n    88→- Events (name, parameters):\n    89→- Where to look:\n    90→\n    91→## Performance/memory (if relevant)\n    92→- What could be affected:\n    93→- What was checked:\n    94→- Results/numbers:\n    95→\n    96→## Risks and limitations\n    97→- Risk:\n    98→- Conditions for occurrence:\n    99→- How to rollback/mitigate:\n   100→\n   101→## Technical debt / follow-up\n   102→- [ ] Task:\n   103→- [ ] Task:\n   104→\n   105→## Notes for reviewer / QA\n   106→- What to pay attention to:\n   107→- Non-standard solutions:\n   108→---\n   109→\n   110→## Quality checklist (before finalizing)\n   111→Before final version check:\n   112→- Are there specific verification steps and expected results?\n   113→- Is it clear which files/modules were changed?\n   114→- Are toggles/settings specified?\n   115→- Are there honest risks/debt if they exist?\n   116→- Can \"what exactly was done\" be reconstructed from the text after 3 months?\n   117→\n   118→## Additional Rules: Fixes After Review / QA\n   119→When to use\n   120→Use this mode if:\n   121→task returned from Review\n   122→task returned from QA\n   123→there were comments in PR/MR\n   124→there were bug reports for current task\n   125→### IMPORTANT: Don't rewrite history\n   126→When fixing comments:\n   127→DO NOT completely rewrite dev_result.md\n   128→DO NOT delete the \"Done\" block\n   129→DO NOT rewrite previous changes\n   130→Instead — add a separate section:\n   131→🛠 Fix Round\n   132→Each fix round should be a separate block:\n   133→```\n   134→## Fix Round #1 (after Review)\n   135→Date:\n   136→Basis: PR link/comment/QA-report link\n   137→\n   138→### Fixed\n   139→- Was:\n   140→- Became:\n   141→- Where changed:\n   142→\n   143→### Reason\n   144→Briefly: why it was initially done this way.\n   145→\n   146→### Side effects\n   147→If affected:\n   148→- API\n   149→- behavior\n   150→- tests\n   151→- performance\n   152→If multiple fixes — add:\n   153→## Fix Round #2 (after QA)\n   154→🧠 Rules for describing fixes\n   155→Always show the difference \"was → became\".\n   156→Specify specific files/classes.\n   157→If tests added — specify which ones.\n   158→If comment rejected — record it:\n   159→### Not accepted\n   160→Comment:\n   161→Decision:\n   162→Rationale:\n   163→If fix could affect logic — update the \"How to verify\" block.\n   164→🔎 If fix is critical\n   165→If fix:\n   166→changes contract\n   167→changes DB schema\n   168→affects production data\n   169→affects performance\n   170→changes feature-flag\n   171→→ Add warning:\n   172→⚠️ Attention:\n   173→Change affects ...\n   174→🧩 Mini-checklist before closing fixes\n   175→Before final version agent must check:\n   176→Are all comments closed?\n   177→Are there updated verification steps?\n   178→Are tests added?\n   179→Is backward compatibility not broken?\n   180→Is it clear what exactly was fixed?\n   181→```\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n",
