→## Status\n   131→Ready for dev - 2026-01-12 12:15:12\n   132→```\n   133→\n   134→### 2. Run Development\n   135→\n   136→Ask Claude to work on the task:\n   137→```\n   138→Work on task MUSIC-009\n   139→```\n   140→\n   141→The plugin will:\n   142→1. Assign the task to `senior-android-developer`\n   143→2. Implement the feature\n   144→3. Run code review via `android-code-reviewer`\n   145→4. Run QA verification via `qa-expert`\n   146→5. Update task status through the workflow\n   147→\n   148→### 3. Track Progress\n   149→\n   150→Task status transitions:\n   151→- `Ready for dev` - Waiting for developer\n   152→- `Dev in progress` - Developer working\n   153→- `Ready for review` - Development complete, waiting for review\n   154→- `Review in progress` - Code review in progress\n   155→- `Ready for QA Review` - Review complete, waiting for QA\n   156→- `QA Review in progress` - QA verification in progress\n   157→- `Verified` - All checks passed\n   158→\n   159→## Task Files\n   160→\n   161→Each task generates several files:\n   162→\n   163→| File | Purpose |\n   164→|------|---------|\n   165→| `task.md` | Task description and status |\n   166→| `dev_result.md` | Development results |\n   167→| `review_result.md` | Code review findings |\n   168→| `qa_review_result.md` | QA verification results |\n   169→\n   170→## Examples\n   171→\n   172→Example files are available in the `skills/*/examples/` directories.\n   173→\n   174→## License\n   175→\n   176→MIT License - see [LICENSE](LICENSE) for details.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n",
